1. nescio quo: Cicero, according to his custom, suppresses the name, though it was well known. Cf. Div. ii. 79 tetra- chiam . . . adseculae suo Pergameno nescio cui dedisset.

nihil . . . necesse: ‘here only in the speeches for non nec. and rare every- where else ’ [Reid].

2. reliqua. auctoritas: ie. quod auc- toritatis reliquum erat senatui, ‘the temnant of authority left to the senate was destroyed.’ Auctoritas is the special attribute of the senate, cf. Leg. iii. 28 auctoritas in senatu sil. All editors interpret auctor. in its technieal sense of a ‘resolution,' sc. fithe rest of the resolu- tion.’ I do not see how sublata agrees with this meaning, since a resolution remained on the minutes, even when it was pre- vented by the veto from beeoming a sen. cons.; cf. Fam. viii. 8. 6 si quis huic s. c. intercesserit, senatui placere auctoritatem perscribi, de Or. iii. 5, &e. For the

tendency of editors to extend this technical
